{"nodes":[{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile and mobile device management (Windows 10)","pos":[11,70]},{"content":"This guide provides an overview of the mobile device and app management technologies in the Windows 10 Mobile operating system.","pos":[84,211]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile and mobile device management","pos":[408,454]},{"content":"Applies to","pos":[458,468]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile","pos":[475,492]},{"content":"This guide provides an overview of the mobile device and app management technologies in the Windows 10 Mobile operating system.","pos":[494,621]},{"content":"It describes how mobile device management (MDM) systems use the built-in device management client to deploy, configure, maintain, and support phones and small tablets running Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[622,815]},{"content":"Bring Your Own Device (BYOD—that is, personal devices) and corporate devices are key scenarios that Windows 10 Mobile MDM capabilities support.","pos":[817,960]},{"content":"The operating system offers a flexible approach to registering devices with directory services and MDM systems, and IT organizations can provision comprehensive device-configuration profiles based on their company’s need to control and secure mobile business data.","pos":[961,1225]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile not only delivers more comprehensive, restrictive configuration settings than Windows Phone 8.1 did but also provides capabilities to deploy and manage apps built on the Universal Windows Platform (UWP).","pos":[1226,1447]},{"content":"Companies can distribute apps directly from Windows Store or by using their MDM system.","pos":[1448,1535]},{"content":"They can control and distribute custom line-of-business (LOB) apps the same way.","pos":[1536,1616]},{"content":"Overview","pos":[1621,1629]},{"content":"Organizations’ users increasingly depend on their mobile devices, but phones and tablets bring new and unfamiliar challenges for IT departments.","pos":[1631,1775]},{"content":"IT must be able to deploy and manage mobile devices and apps quickly to support the business while balancing the growing need to protect corporate data because of evolving laws, regulations, and cybercrime.","pos":[1776,1982]},{"content":"IT must ensure that the apps and data on those mobile devices are safe, especially on personal devices.","pos":[1983,2086]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile helps organizations address these challenges by providing a robust, flexible, built-in MDM client.","pos":[2087,2203]},{"content":"IT departments can use the MDM system of their choice to manage this client.","pos":[2204,2280]},{"pos":[2328,2347],"content":"Built-in MDM client"},{"content":"The built-in MDM client is common to all editions of the Windows 10 operating system, including desktop, mobile, and Internet of Things (IoT).","pos":[2349,2491]},{"content":"The client provides a single interface through which you can manage any device that runs Windows 10.","pos":[2492,2592]},{"content":"The client has two important roles: device enrollment in an MDM system and device management.","pos":[2593,2686]},{"content":"Device enrollment.","pos":[2694,2712]},{"content":"Users can enroll in the MDM system.","pos":[2715,2750]},{"content":"On Windows 10, a user can register a device with Microsoft Azure Active Directory (Azure AD) and enroll in an MDM system at the same time so that the system can manage the device, the apps running on it, and the confidential data it holds.","pos":[2751,2990]},{"content":"Enrollment establishes the management authority for the device.","pos":[2991,3054]},{"content":"Only one management authority (or MDM enrollment) is possible at a time, which helps prevent unauthorized access to devices and ensures their stability and reliability.","pos":[3055,3223]},{"content":"Device management.","pos":[3230,3248]},{"content":"The MDM client allows the MDM system to configure policy settings; deploy apps and updates; and perform other management tasks, such as remotely wiping the device.","pos":[3251,3414]},{"content":"The MDM system sends configuration requests and collects inventory through the MDM client.","pos":[3415,3505]},{"content":"The client uses <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>configuration service providers (CSPs)<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=734049)</ept> to configure and inventory settings.","pos":[3506,3648]},{"content":"A CSP is an interface to read, set, modify, or delete configuration settings on the device.","pos":[3649,3740]},{"content":"These settings map to registry keys or files.","pos":[3741,3786]},{"content":"(The security architecture of Windows 10 Mobile prevents direct access to registry settings and operating system files.","pos":[3787,3906]},{"content":"For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows 10 Mobile security guide<ept id=\"p1\">](../keep-secure/windows-10-mobile-security-guide.md)</ept>.)","pos":[3907,4025]},{"content":"The MDM client is an integral part of Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[4027,4083]},{"content":"As a result, there is no need for an additional, custom MDM app to enroll the device or to allow an MDM system to manage it.","pos":[4084,4208]},{"content":"All MDM systems have equal access to Windows 10 Mobile MDM application programming interfaces (APIs), so you can choose Microsoft Intune or a third-party MDM product to manage Windows 10 Mobile devices.","pos":[4209,4411]},{"content":"For more information about Windows 10 Mobile device management APIs, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Mobile device management<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=734050)</ept>.","pos":[4412,4561]},{"pos":[4602,4628],"content":"Windows 10 Mobile editions"},{"content":"Every device that runs Windows 10 Mobile includes all the enterprise mobile device security and management capabilities the MDM client provides.","pos":[4630,4774]},{"content":"Microsoft also offers an Enterprise edition of Windows 10 Mobile, which includes three additional capabilities.","pos":[4775,4886]},{"content":"To enable these capabilities, you can provision a license file without reinstalling the operating system:","pos":[4887,4992]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Ability to postpone software updates.<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>Windows 10 Mobile gets software updates directly from Windows Update, and you cannot curate updates prior to deployment.","pos":[4998,5159]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile Enterprise, however, allows you to curate and validate updates prior to deploying them.","pos":[5160,5265]},{"content":"No limit on the number of self-signed LOB apps that you can deploy to a single device.","pos":[5272,5358]},{"content":"To use an MDM system to deploy LOB apps directly to devices, you must cryptographically sign the software packages with a code signing certificate that your organization’s certificate authority (CA) generates.","pos":[5361,5570]},{"content":"You can deploy a maximum of 20 self-signed LOB apps to a Windows 10 Mobile device, more than 20 if your organization’s devices run Windows 10 Mobile Enterprise.","pos":[5571,5731]},{"content":"Set telemetry to security level.","pos":[5738,5770]},{"content":"The telemetry security level configures the operating system to gather only the telemetry information required to keep devices secured.","pos":[5773,5908]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Your organization can opt to purchase a code signing certificate from Verisign to sign LOB apps or use <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Windows Store for Business<ept id=\"p2\">](windows-store-for-business.md)</ept> to obtain apps.","pos":[5911,6100]},{"content":"With either method, you can distribute more than 20 apps to a single device without activating Windows 10 Mobile Enterprise on that device by using your MDM system.","pos":[6101,6265]},{"content":"To activate Windows 10 Mobile Enterprise on any Windows 10 Mobile device, use your company’s MDM system or a provisioning package to inject a license onto the device.","pos":[6268,6434]},{"content":"You can download a Windows 10 Mobile Enterprise license from the Business Support Portal.","pos":[6435,6524]},{"pos":[6573,6593],"content":"Lifecycle management"},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile supports end-to-end lifecycle device management to give companies control of their devices, data, and apps.","pos":[6595,6720]},{"content":"Comprehensive MDM systems use the built-in MDM client to manage devices throughout their lifecycle, as Figure 1 illustrates.","pos":[6721,6845]},{"content":"The remainder of this guide describes the operating system’s mobile device and app management capabilities through each phase of the lifecycle, showing how MDM systems use specific features.","pos":[6846,7036]},{"content":"figure 1","pos":[7040,7048]},{"content":"Figure 1.","pos":[7085,7094]},{"content":"Device management lifecycle","pos":[7095,7122]},{"pos":[7167,7184],"content":"Device deployment"},{"content":"Device deployment includes the initial registration and configuration of the device, including its enrollment with an MDM system.","pos":[7186,7315]},{"content":"Sometimes, companies preinstall apps.","pos":[7316,7353]},{"content":"The major factors in how you deploy devices and which controls you put in place are device ownership and how the user will use the device.","pos":[7354,7492]},{"content":"This guide covers two scenarios:","pos":[7493,7525]},{"pos":[7531,7719],"content":"Companies allow users to personalize their devices because the users own the devices or because company policy doesn’t require tight controls (defined as <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>personal devices<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in this guide)."},{"pos":[7724,7946],"content":"Companies don’t allow users to personalize their devices or they limit personalization, usually because the organization owns the devices and security considerations are high (defined as <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>corporate devices<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in this guide)."},{"content":"Often, employees can choose devices from a list of supported models, or companies provide devices that they preconfigure, or bootstrap, with a baseline configuration.","pos":[7948,8114]},{"content":"Microsoft recommends Azure AD Join and MDM enrollment and management for corporate devices and Azure AD Registration and MDM enrollment and management for personal devices.","pos":[8116,8288]},{"pos":[8337,8357],"content":"Deployment scenarios"},{"content":"Most organizations support both personal and corporate device scenarios.","pos":[8359,8431]},{"content":"The infrastructure for these scenarios is similar, but the deployment process and configuration policies differ.","pos":[8432,8544]},{"content":"Table 1 describes characteristics of the personal and corporate device scenarios.","pos":[8545,8626]},{"content":"Activation of a device with an organizational identity is unique to Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[8627,8713]},{"content":"Table 1.","pos":[8715,8723]},{"content":"Characteristics of personal and corporate device scenarios","pos":[8724,8782]},{"content":"Personal devices","pos":[8940,8956]},{"content":"Corporate devices","pos":[8979,8996]},{"content":"Ownership","pos":[9043,9052]},{"content":"User","pos":[9075,9079]},{"content":"Organization","pos":[9102,9114]},{"content":"Primary use","pos":[9160,9171]},{"content":"Personal","pos":[9194,9202]},{"content":"Work","pos":[9225,9229]},{"content":"Deployment","pos":[9276,9286]},{"content":"The primary identity on the device is a personal identity.","pos":[9309,9367]},{"content":"A Microsoft account is the default option for Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[9368,9432]},{"content":"The primary identity on the device is an organizational identity.","pos":[9455,9520]},{"content":"An Azure AD account is the default option for Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[9521,9585]},{"pos":[9663,9682],"content":"Identity management"},{"content":"People can use only one account to activate a device, so it’s imperative that your organization control which account you enable first.","pos":[9684,9819]},{"content":"The account you choose will determine who controls the device and influence your management capabilities.","pos":[9820,9925]},{"content":"The following list describes the impact that users’ identities have on management (Table 2 summarizes these considerations):","pos":[9926,10050]},{"content":"Personal identity.","pos":[10058,10076]},{"content":"In this scenario, employees use their Microsoft account to activate the device.","pos":[10079,10158]},{"content":"Then, they use their Azure AD account (organizational identity) to register the device in Azure AD and enroll it with the company’s MDM solution.","pos":[10159,10304]},{"content":"You can apply policies to help protect and contain corporate apps and data on the devices, designed to prevent intellectual property leaks, but users keep full control over personal activities, such as downloading and installing apps and games.","pos":[10305,10549]},{"content":"Organizational identity.","pos":[10556,10580]},{"content":"In this scenario, employees use their Azure AD account to register the device to Azure AD and automatically enroll it with the organization’s MDM solution.","pos":[10583,10738]},{"content":"In this case, companies can block personal use of devices.","pos":[10739,10797]},{"content":"Using organizational Identities to initialize devices gives organizations complete control over devices and allows them to prevent personalization.","pos":[10798,10945]},{"content":"Table 2.","pos":[10947,10955]},{"content":"Personal vs. organizational identity","pos":[10956,10992]},{"content":"Personal identity","pos":[11150,11167]},{"content":"Corporate identity","pos":[11190,11208]},{"content":"First account on the device","pos":[11255,11282]},{"content":"Microsoft account","pos":[11305,11322]},{"content":"Azure AD account","pos":[11345,11361]},{"content":"Device sign-in","pos":[11407,11421]},{"content":"Users cannot sign in to devices with Azure AD credentials, even if they add the credentials after initial activation with a Microsoft account.","pos":[11444,11586]},{"content":"Users can unlock devices with an Azure AD account.","pos":[11609,11659]},{"content":"Organizations can block the addition of a personal identity.","pos":[11660,11720]},{"content":"User settings and data roaming across devices","pos":[11767,11812]},{"content":"User and app settings roam across devices activated with the same personal identity over personal OneDrive.","pos":[11835,11942]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile currently does not support users and app settings roaming over the enterprise cloud.","pos":[11965,12067]},{"content":"It can block the roaming of personal cloud settings.","pos":[12068,12120]},{"content":"Ability to block the use of a personal identity on the device","pos":[12166,12227]},{"content":"No","pos":[12250,12252]},{"content":"Yes","pos":[12275,12278]},{"content":"Level of control","pos":[12325,12341]},{"content":"Organization can apply most* restrictive policies to devices, but they cannot remove the Microsoft account from them.","pos":[12367,12484]},{"content":"Device users can reclaim full control over their devices by un-enrolling them from the organization’s MDM solution.","pos":[12485,12600]},{"content":"Note","pos":[12633,12637]},{"content":"MDM functionality on personal devices might be limited in the future.","pos":[12654,12723]},{"content":"Organizations are free to apply the restrictive policies to devices that policy standards and compliance regulations require and prevent the user from un-enrolling the device from the enterprise.","pos":[12772,12967]},{"pos":[13053,13080],"content":"Infrastructure requirements"},{"content":"For both device scenarios, the essential infrastructure and tools required to deploy and manage Windows 10 Mobile devices include an Azure AD subscription and an MDM system.","pos":[13082,13255]},{"content":"Azure AD is a cloud-based directory service that provides identity and access management.","pos":[13257,13346]},{"content":"You can integrate it with existing on-premises directories to create a hybrid solution.","pos":[13347,13434]},{"content":"Azure AD has three editions: Free, Basic, and Premium (see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Active Directory editions<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723980)</ept>).","pos":[13435,13578]},{"content":"All editions support Azure AD device registration, but the Premium edition is required to enable MDM auto-enrollment and conditional access based on device state.","pos":[13579,13741]},{"content":"Organizations that use Microsoft Office 365 or Intune are already using Azure AD.","pos":[13742,13823]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Most industry-leading MDM vendors already support integration with Azure AD or are working on integration.","pos":[13826,13943]},{"content":"You can find the MDM vendors that support Azure AD in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Marketplace<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723981)</ept>.","pos":[13944,14067]},{"content":"Users can enroll Windows 10 Mobile devices in third-party MDM systems without using an Azure AD organizational account.","pos":[14070,14189]},{"content":"(By default, Intune uses Azure AD and includes a license).","pos":[14190,14248]},{"content":"If your organization doesn’t use Azure AD, you must use a personal identity to activate devices and enable common scenarios, such as downloading apps from Windows Store.","pos":[14249,14418]},{"content":"Multiple MDM systems that support Windows 10 Mobile are available.","pos":[14420,14486]},{"content":"Most support personal and corporate device deployment scenarios.","pos":[14487,14551]},{"content":"Microsoft offers <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Intune<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723983)</ept>, which is part of the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Enterprise Mobility Suite<ept id=\"p2\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723984)</ept> and a cloud-based MDM system that manages devices off premises.","pos":[14552,14789]},{"content":"Like Office 365, Intune uses Azure AD for identity management, so employees use the same credentials to enroll devices in Intune or sign in to Office 365.","pos":[14790,14944]},{"content":"Intune supports devices that run other operating systems, as well, such as iOS and Android, to provide a complete MDM solution.","pos":[14945,15072]},{"content":"You can also integrate Intune with System Center Configuration Manager to gain a single console in which to manage all devices—in the cloud and on premises.","pos":[15074,15230]},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Manage Mobile Devices with Configuration Manager and Microsoft Intune<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=734051)</ept>.","pos":[15231,15378]},{"content":"For guidance on choosing between a stand-alone Intune installation and Intune integrated with Configuration Manager, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Choose between Intune by itself or integrating Intune with System Center Configuration Manager<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723985)</ept>.","pos":[15379,15646]},{"content":"In addition to Intune, other MDM providers support Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[15647,15716]},{"content":"Currently, the following MDM systems claim to support Windows 10 and Windows 10 Mobile: <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>AirWatch<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723986)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Citrix<ept id=\"p2\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723987)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Lightspeed Systems<ept id=\"p3\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723988)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt>Matrix42<ept id=\"p4\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723989)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt>MobileIron<ept id=\"p5\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723990)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p6\">[</bpt>SAP<ept id=\"p6\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723991)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p7\">[</bpt>SOTI<ept id=\"p7\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723992)</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p8\">[</bpt>Symantec<ept id=\"p8\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=723993)</ept>.","pos":[15717,16297]},{"content":"All MDM vendors have equal access to the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows 10 MDM APIs<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=734050)</ept>.","pos":[16299,16411]},{"content":"The extent to which they implement these APIs depends on the vendor.","pos":[16412,16480]},{"content":"Contact your preferred MDM vendor to determine its level of support.","pos":[16481,16549]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Although not covered in this guide, you can use Exchange ActiveSync (EAS) to manage mobile devices instead of using a full-featured MDM system.","pos":[16552,16706]},{"content":"EAS is available in Microsoft Exchange Server 2010 or later and Office 365.","pos":[16707,16782]},{"content":"In addition, Microsoft recently added MDM capabilities powered by Intune to Office 365.","pos":[16783,16870]},{"content":"MDM for Office 365 supports mobile devices only, such as those running Windows 10 Mobile, iOS, and Android.","pos":[16871,16978]},{"content":"MDM for Office 365 offers a subset of the management capabilities found in Intune, including the ability to remotely wipe a device, block a device from accessing Exchange Server email, and configure device policies (for example, passcode requirements).","pos":[16979,17231]},{"content":"For more information about MDM for Office 365 capabilities, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Overview of Mobile Device Management for Office 365<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=734052)</ept>.","pos":[17232,17399]},{"pos":[17441,17453],"content":"Provisioning"},{"content":"Provisioning is new to Windows 10 and uses the MDM client in Windows 10 Mobile.","pos":[17455,17534]},{"content":"You can create a runtime provisioning package to apply settings, profiles, and file assets to a device running Windows 10.","pos":[17535,17657]},{"content":"To assist users with MDM system enrollment, use a provisioning package.","pos":[17658,17729]},{"content":"To do so, use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=733911)</ept> to create a provisioning package, and then install that package on the device.","pos":[17730,17920]},{"content":"Users can perform self-service MDM enrollment based on the following deployment scenarios:","pos":[17921,18011]},{"content":"Corporate device.","pos":[18019,18036]},{"content":"During the out-of-the-box experience (OOBE), you can instruct the user to select <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>This device is owned by my organization<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and join the device to Azure AD and the MDM system.","pos":[18039,18215]},{"content":"Personal device.","pos":[18222,18238]},{"content":"The user activates the device with a Microsoft account, but you can instruct him or her to register the device with Azure AD and enroll in Intune.","pos":[18241,18387]},{"content":"To do so in Windows 10 Mobile, the user clicks, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Settings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, clicks <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Accounts<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, and then clicks <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Work access<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>.","pos":[18388,18503]},{"content":"To automate MDM enrollment, use provisioning packages as follows:","pos":[18504,18569]},{"content":"Corporate device.","pos":[18576,18593]},{"content":"You can create a provisioning package and apply it to a corporate device before delivery to the user, or instruct the user to apply the package during OOBE.","pos":[18596,18752]},{"content":"After application of the provisioning package, the OOBE process automatically chooses the enterprise path and requires the user to register the device with Azure AD and enroll it in the MDM system.","pos":[18753,18950]},{"content":"Personal device.","pos":[18957,18973]},{"content":"You can create a provisioning package and make it available to users who want to enroll their personal device in the enterprise.","pos":[18976,19104]},{"content":"The user enrolls the device in the corporate MDM for further configuration by applying the provisioning package.","pos":[19105,19217]},{"content":"To do so in Windows 10 Mobile, the user clicks <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Settings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, clicks <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Accounts<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, and then clicks <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Provisioning<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>).","pos":[19218,19334]},{"content":"Distribute provisioning packages to devices by publishing them in an easily accessible location (e.g., an email attachment or a web page).","pos":[19336,19474]},{"content":"You can cryptographically sign or encrypt provisioning packages and require that the user enter a password to apply them.","pos":[19475,19596]},{"pos":[19598,19747],"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Build and apply a provisioning package<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=734054)</ept> for more information on creating provisioning packages."},{"content":"Device configuration","pos":[19752,19772]},{"content":"The following sections describe the device configuration capabilities of the built-in Windows 10 Mobile MDM client.","pos":[19774,19889]},{"content":"This client exposes the capabilities to any MDM system compatible with Windows 10.","pos":[19890,19972]},{"content":"Configurable settings include:","pos":[19973,20003]},{"content":"Email accounts","pos":[20010,20024]},{"content":"Account restrictions","pos":[20039,20059]},{"content":"Device lock restrictions","pos":[20081,20105]},{"content":"Hardware restrictions","pos":[20126,20147]},{"content":"Certificate management","pos":[20165,20187]},{"content":"Wi-Fi","pos":[20208,20213]},{"content":"Proxy","pos":[20227,20232]},{"content":"Virtual private network (VPN)","pos":[20247,20276]},{"content":"Access point name (APN) profiles","pos":[20289,20321]},{"content":"Data leak prevention","pos":[20334,20354]},{"content":"Storage management","pos":[20368,20386]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Although all the MDM settings this section describes are available in Windows 10 Mobile, not all MDM systems may show them in their user interface.","pos":[20400,20558]},{"content":"In addition, naming may vary among MDM systems.","pos":[20559,20606]},{"content":"Consult your MDM system’s documentation for more information.","pos":[20607,20668]},{"pos":[20701,20715],"content":"Email accounts"},{"content":"You can use your corporate MDM system to manage corporate email accounts.","pos":[20717,20790]},{"content":"Define email account profiles in the MDM system, and then deploy them to devices.","pos":[20791,20872]},{"content":"You would usually deploy these settings immediately after enrollment, regardless of scenario.","pos":[20873,20966]},{"content":"This capability extends to email systems that use EAS.","pos":[20968,21022]},{"content":"Table 3 lists settings that you can configure in EAS email profiles.","pos":[21023,21091]},{"content":"Table 3.","pos":[21093,21101]},{"content":"Windows 10 Mobile settings for EAS email profiles","pos":[21102,21151]},{"content":"Setting","pos":[21155,21162]},{"content":"Description","pos":[21184,21195]},{"content":"Email Address","pos":[21595,21608]},{"content":"The email address associated with the EAS account","pos":[21624,21673]},{"content":"Domain","pos":[21815,21821]},{"content":"The domain name of the Exchange Server instance","pos":[21844,21891]},{"content":"Account Name","pos":[22035,22047]},{"content":"A user-friendly name for the email account on the device","pos":[22064,22120]},{"content":"Password","pos":[22255,22263]},{"content":"The password for the email account","pos":[22284,22318]},{"content":"Server Name","pos":[22475,22486]},{"content":"The server name that the email account uses","pos":[22504,22547]},{"content":"User Name","pos":[22695,22704]},